SIMPLE: intercalary
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intercalary
<hw>In*ter"ca*la*ry</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intercalaris</ets>, <ets>intercalarius</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>intercalaire</ets>. See <er>Intercalate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chron.)</fld> <def>Inserted or introduced among
others in the calendar; <as>as, an <ex>intercalary</ex> month, day,
etc.</as>; -- now applied particularly to the odd day (Feb. 29) inserted
in the calendar of leap year. See <er>Bissextile</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Introduced or inserted among others; additional;
supernumerary.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Intercalary</xex> spines.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Owen.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>intercalary</qex> line . . . is made the last of a
triplet.</q> <rj><qau>Beattie.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Intercalary day</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>one on
which no paroxysm of an intermittent disease occurs.</cd>
<rj><au>Mayne.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intercalate</ent>⟦br⟧
